1. Executive Summary ¶

1.1 Objective ¶

The objective of this Capstone Project is to predict the severity levels in the vehicle accidents in France. For this analysis, I took the data between 2019 and 2022.

1.2 Problem ¶

Knowing that the initial project is to prevent more vehicles accidents per year, it will be useful to predict the kind of severity when an accident is produced. Based on that, the future actions could be taken in place to decrease the severities of accidents. This analysis could be useful as a criteria for assurance companies to estimate the assurances prices too.

1.3 Solution ¶

The solution includes several steps:


  1. Import of the data source: Base on the public source data.gouv.fr [1]
  2. Preprocessing of the data: Conversion of some fields and deletion of not necessary fields
  3. Analysis of the data: Pairplots, correlation analysis and filtering of values
  4. Split of the data and scaling
  5. Modelling: I used the following algorithms to compare and get the results: K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN), Linear Support Vector Machines (Linear SVM), Decision Trees, Random Forest, Light Gradient-Boosting Machine (LGBM) and eXtreme Gradient-Boosting (XGBoost)
  6. Those results included the comparison for two ways: multiclass and binary output
  7. For the hyperparameter tuning, the used of Halving Grid Search CV accelarated the search of parameter candidates to find the best accuracy.

1.4 Value Proposition ¶

The results could be used to prevent future vehicle accidents and even used as a reference in the estimation of vehicles assurances.

1.5 Findings and Conclusion ¶

The analysis revealed the following results:

  1. The multiclass classification did not reveal very good results because the severity levels "killed" and "injured hospitalized" are not frequently present in the data collected.
  2. A good way to analyze the severity level is using binary severity classification: "without physical damaged" and "with physical damage". This increased a lot the results of our results for the algorithms analyzed
  3. XGBoost classification showed to be the algorithm best adapted to this case: Precision of 82% and AUC of 0.9
  4. There are more improvements that could be used in this project: included more regions and used other sources to complement the data and improve the accuracy (geographic and demographic information).

2. Introduction ¶

During the Capstone Project, I used the different knowledge studied in this course and apply it in a Study Case, I decided to analyze the different accidents in France between 2019 and 2022.


The objective of this project is being able to predict the severity level of the accidents produced in France in the mostly visited places in France.
Due to the constraints of time and computing, I only opted to analyze some departments in France, including Ile-de-France.

The different files contained key values that I joined them. After this, all those dataframes were fusioned in one dataframe and they were used to the following step.

3.4 Data Preparation for modeling ¶

For that step, two actions were performed:


1. Convert categorical variables: I used the get_dummies method and it will accelerate the process when we need to see the important features to take into account 2. Standardization of the data: That it is an important step because it will reduce the impact of outliers in our analysis and improve the performance of the ML models

3.5 Multiclass and binary severity levels ¶

For the multiclass severity level, I kept the same values defined in the data and it will not impact the results.


For the binary sverity lvel, due to the complexity to predict the severity with more accuracy, I will modelize the data by grouping in two results: * 1 : Without any physical problem: Converted to 0 * 2, 3, 4 : With a physical problem (including minor accident until death): Converted to 1 That approach was based too in the following report based on work on Severity predictions for older years [[2](#reference-2)]
The histogram of the binary severity level could be seen in the Figure 13.

Figure 13. Histogram of severity levels in binary level

3.6 ML Models and Hyperparameter tuning ¶

In this capstone, I used the following ML Classification models:

  1. K-Nearest Neighbors: One of the first ML models used and it will used to mainly compare it with the other ML models
  2. Support Vector Machines: For this case I used the Linear SVM Classification model (linear_svc in Pyhon) because it supports a large amount of data and the processing time is much faster than the library svm
  3. Decision Tree
  4. Random Forest
  5. Light Gradient-Boosting Machine (LGBM): A model based on Gradient Boosting
  6. eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost): A model based on Gradient Boosting

For the hyperparameter tuning, to accelerate the processing time, I used an experimental library which is known like Halving Grid Search CV. It implements a succesive halving of candidates based on multiple iterations. Each iteration increases the amount of ressources but reduces the number of candidates and some candidates are used in the last iteration [4]. A description of this is shown in the Figure 14, where the number of candidates is reduced on each iteration and the mean test score increases.

Figure 14. Halving Grid Search CV example. Source: Skit-learn.org

Other important thing to analyze is the Feature Importance diagram. For the case of multiclass classification (Figure 23), it reveals interesting things:

  1. Firstly, in the accidents, people were using belt and helmet but they were using other security equipment which has not been identified.
  2. The walker variable had relevance to identify the severity levels and the place of the accident is important too.
  3. The manouver of turning left and opening door have important relevances in the accidents.
  4. However, some people were not using security equipment during the accident which could imply a modification of the severity level.
  5. The urban area and the Municipal road are variables to discriminate the severity level.
  6. The presence of not obstacle in the vehicle accident is an important factor to take into account too.

Figure 23. Top 35 Feature Importance Graphic - XGBoost Classifier - Severity multiclass level

For the case of binary classification (Figure 24), showed important modifications in comparison to the multiclass classification:

  1. The use of gants is showed as a variable to discriminate the severity level.
  2. The use of not security equipment took a lot of relevance to discriminate the severity level too.
  3. The use of the utility vehicle has escalated as a very important variable too.

Figure 24. Top 35 Feature Importance Graphic - XGBoost Classifier - Severity binary level

In both cases there are variables that are surprisingly not considered so relevant:

  1. Maximum authorized speed: Which it means security equipment had much more importance in comparison to the speed to decrease the severity level. It could sound counterintuitive but, during the vehicle accident, if the driver has respected the speed limit, the security equipment could help him to decrease his severity level.
  2. Latitude and longitude: Similar to the maximum authorized speed, during the vehicle accident, if the drive has respected the rules, that variable will not take so much relevance.

Finally, It does not mean we do not take into account those variables, it means that the drivers were respecting mostly the security rules. If they did not respect them, I think the Feature Importance graphic could have changed radically.

5. Conclusion ¶

The analysis revealed the following results:

  1. The multiclass classification did not reveal very good results because the severity levels "killed" and "injured hospitalized" are not frequently present in the data collected.
  2. A good way to analyze the severity level is using binary severity classification: "without physical damaged" and "with physical damage". This increased a lot the results of our results for the algorithms analyzed
  3. XGBoost classification showed to be the algorithm best adapted to this case: Precision of 82% and AUC of 0.9
  4. There are more improvements that could be used in this project: included more regions and used other sources to complement the data and improve the accuracy (geographic and demographic information).
